Though you may not have realized it, 2013 entirely changed the course of popular music. More specifically, THREE records from 2013 entirely changed the course of popular music.

In the five or so years leading up to 2013 we saw indie and alternative music boom, with many artists embracing keyboards and synths with fervour. Big hooks, big drums, big choruses - maximalist pop was the name of the game, and even bands that skewed folk stylistically still operated with a big arena mindset. 

In 2013 things changed when Daft Punk, a duo known for futuristic and avant-garde fusion, decided to troll everyone and release ‘Random Access Memories’. Other than a few light electronic touches, it was essentially a funk record, and everyone wanted to get funky after that. Just a few months later we got Arcade Fire’s ‘Reflektor’ which followed suit and cemented the funk revival of the 2010s. 

Another popular direction for artists was to get smoky like Arctic Monkeys. 'AM' brought out the lounge lizard in many artists both alternative and pop, a throwback feel reverberating to this day as we see with many of pop's soft boys embracing the prickly guitars and vintage crooning.

And then there was Lorde’s ‘Pure Heroine’, without which we would not have Billie Eilish or any number of darkly minimalist acts today. It directly rebuked every single pop trope from the previous 5 years, with Lorde literally singing she didn’t want to put her hands up in the air and party.

These records went far beyond affecting genre though; they changed the mentality of the music industry. Even if bands didn’t adopt one of these genres, many, many adopted the idea of “recording organically”. In the following years songs got a little rougher, the drums a little drier, the distortion guitars a little dirtier - all elements still regularly sought after in music today. It was no longer popular to experiment with futuristic dubstep squelches that evoked robot music from 2043. Now it was all about the record hiss, the live drums, and the unprocessed vocals of 1973. 

Though you didn’t see all the changes immediately, 2013 was the beginning of “out with the hi-fi, in with the lo-fi.”
It’s the table of misfit chocolates.

There were so many big albums celebrating 20 year anniversaries in 2023 we had to make two slides to list them. Two slides!

2003 was a year right on the cusp of change. Nu metal and hard rock were still dominating the alternative music scene, with garage rock close behind. But slowly, very slowly, you had emo artists beginning to crop up more often, usurping pop punk. 

And alongside them came the indie bands who would get a massive bump in popularity thanks to teen soap The OC that debuted that fall. The true big flip wouldn't happen until about halfway through 2004 - but we'll get to that next year.

Also, anybody else remember ZWAN??

Looking back at the charts of 1998, the first thing that pops out to us is the massive amount of big hits that came out of one year. 

But the second thing that pops out to is is how many of those hits would end up being those bands' only BIG song. By sheer popularity alone, 1998 may have had the most recognizable one-hit wonders of the decade.

Do you remember all the songs on the second slide?

By 2003 nu-metal and nu-metal adjacent hard rock acts were well-entrenched in the mainstream. Bands like Linkin Park, Staind, Deftones, and Finger Eleven were already institutions with successful albums under their belts. It would take something special for a band to try and break into a scene already over 5 years in the public eye. 

Three Days Grace were that something special, proving themselves over and over with multiple hit albums over the following decade. And it all started with their self-titled debut, released on this day 20 years ago. With the perfect combination of distortion guitars and existential angst, the Norwood, Ontario band became known around the world with their first few singles like "Just Like You", "Home", "Wake Up", and of course "I Hate Everything About You".
